@node "The" "About The Guide"


  In this guide you will find all the information needed to start playing
 in the Email/Netmail based game 'Insignia of Terror', which is GM'd by
 myself, the author of both Arcane Lore and Mystic systems. This guide does
 NOT contain the information required for you to run your own campaign, or
 create your own Mystic RPG based game. If after reading this you do want
 to use the GM's rules, there is a section later that informs you of the
 various options available.

  This guide should be understandable for even a complete beginner to
 RPGing, and I hope this doesn't put off any of the veterans out there.
 I've done this to make the game as user friendly as possible, as when it
 comes down to it, the point of any game is to be entertained. Pages of
 jargon aren't entertaining to the average potential player.

  So, as this is the play by netmail/email starter pack for Insignia Of
 Terror, it contains all the info you need to get your character(s) up and
 running in the game world. It covers all the procedures you need to go
 through to pick your character's race and class, and informs you how the
 mechanics of this remotely refereed game work.

  As you read you'll learn it's not as complicated as it first seems. And
 if you've never role-played before I'll make you into an expert in no
 time. Oh, and another point I think I should make. Don't panic! This
 guide may appear very bulky, but you only really need to read some of it.
 I'll leave it up to you to decide how much you're going to read, because
 what you should read depends entirely on what type of character you want
 to play.


@endnode

@node "WhRPG" "What IS an RPG?"


  An important question, that needs to be answered. An RPG or Role-
 Playing Game is essentially a game in which the player or players
 have to act, or play out the part of a pre-created character. In a
 traditional RPG this means trying to think your character's way out
 of situations, and acting as your character to communicate with Non
 Player Characters (NPCs). NPCs are controlled by the Games Master
 (GM), as is everything else in the game world excluding the Player
 Characters (PCs), who are controlled by the players as said above.
 No real definition of RPG exists, and it's meaning is extremely
 debatable. Some would argue that an RPG must have at least two
 players, although many single player 'RPG' books and computer games
 exist.


@endnode

@node "ImAb" "Important Words & Abbreviations"


  To avoid confusion in the early stages I have listed all the very common
 abbreviations and game words that you will come across in this guide:

 Arcane Lore: A detailed RPG system that I run only as a standard paper
     (AL)     based system.

 Mystic: Basic Arcane Lore, the system used in Insignia Of Terror.

 Insignia Of Terror: The name of the game you are about to take place in.
        (IOT)        As said above, the Mystic rules system is used.

 GM: The Games Master, or referee.. In Mystic he/she is called simply
     'The Master'.

 PC: No, not the computer (thank ye lords!) but a Player Character. This
     is what you'll be controlling one of when you start playing IOT.

 NPC: Non-Player Character. These are controlled by the GM, in this case
      me.

 Test: When a random number is used to decide the result of an action in
       the game.. As a general rule tests are decided by dice rolls.


@endnode

@node "Game" "About Mystic RPG"


  I started writing Mystic in mid 1996. I needed an easy and fun system
 that worked alongside my other, more complex system, Arcane Lore. I had
 to make sure I included all the correct information and rules. Making a
 good, simple system is much harder than making a good complex one.

  The following is a short history of the Arcane Lore system:

   1992-93: Old form of Arcane Lore paper based system created,
            whole idea behind project being it had to be VERY simple.
      1993: Reconsidered design, started adding detailed rules, as the
            rules were very restrictive.
      1994: Completely redesigned the mechanics, to allow the extra rules
            without slowing the system down. It was now a complex system.
      1995: Gave it the name Arcane Lore, and found no need to change the
            game mechanics. It seemed to work very well now.
      1996: Opened up the play by Email version of Insignia Of Terror to
            playtesters. This proved successful. Development began on
            Mystic, a basic version of AL that would be more suitable
            for combat oriented games, and Insignia Of Terror.
      1997: Development of Mystic completed, relaunch of Insignia Of
            Terror to old playtesters and new players. Now IOT uses
            Mystic's rules exclusively.

  Designing Mystic has not been as difficult as I had expected. Actually
 the process has been quite enjoyable. The system is basically a cross
 between the very first version of Arcane Lore, and a simplified version
 of the most up-to-date one. Looking back at work I did that long ago
 made me realise how far the system has come since then. The first
 version was weird to say the least, and although the ideas were simple,
 the methods used for usual things like character generation were very
 obscure!

 So now we have the two systems:

  Mystic: for IOT and paper based campaigns where masses of rules aren't
 important.

  Arcane Lore: For paper based campaigns where detail is a factor. I will
 not GM IOT under Arcane Lore rules as it is a complex system, and would
 take up a lot more time to GM and play than needed.


@endnode

@node "IOT" "About Insignia Of Terror"


  Insignia of Terror was an idea I had, soon after I started out in the
 world of comms. I realised that there was such a vast gap to fill where
 RPG gaming was concerned, and I had already designed the perfect system
 for it! I quickly adapted the advanced Arcane Lore system to work over
 netmail on a local network, and opened it for play by anyone there who
 wished to playtest it in those early stages. It worked excellently, with
 only one main problem. Because it used the hefty Arcane Lore system it
 took up masses of my time to GM. I had to stop and rethink my strategy.
 After a great deal of thought it occurred to me that if I designed a more
 basic system it would save a lot of my time, and be more fun to the
 general player. I set to work on the system now known as Mystic, and now
 it's complete I have altered Insignia Of Terror to use these rules.

  Why Insignia Of Terror? Well, there is an important reason for this
 name, but I won't go into it now. You should be able to work out the
 title after reading some of the world's background information.


@endnode

@node "Basics" "Basics of Insignia Of Terror"


  In Insignia Of Terror the main part of your gaming time is taken up by
 communication with both PCs and NPCs. It is not a combat frenzy, and all
 characters start their adventuring career in the same town, making party
 formation a lot easier.

  The game runs in the following way:

   1  You get this guide from me.
   2  You follow the character creation process detailed in this guide.
   3  You send your character details back to me.
   4  I finish the character generation.
   5  I send you the finished character profile, and your first turn sheet.
   6  You fill in the turn sheet, and send it back.
   7  I reply to your turn sheet.
   8  You reply to that.
   9  Repeat steps 7 and 8 until you stop playing.

  All these steps are explained fully in this guide.

  IOT is a completely open-ended game.. This means that there is no single
 'mission' you have to complete before the game ends. Think of it in
 this way.. Tharthaal, the town your character lives in is a real place,
 where real people live. When you die or stop playing, the world doesn't
 'stop'.. Neither does it end when you've achieved your goals. You
 basically 'are' a person in the fantasy world for an amount of time in
 their life. Perhaps difficult to grasp, but it's fairly simple once
 you've got the general idea. Also, IOT has complete freedom of movement.
 There is no set way you have to play, and virtually no restrictions on
 how you write your replies. So, in effect, you can write a message
 telling  me  you  want  your character to dance a jig then hit their head
 against the wall three times, and it would happen in the game.

  IMPORTANT: turns are calculated twice a week.


@endnode

