@node "Stats" "Statistics and their meanings"


  Statistics are numbers that show how good your character is in certain
 areas. When the character wants to do something difficult or unusual, a
 test is made against the respective statistic. For example, if the
 character had to hold up a collapsing corridor so that his friends could
 pass, a Strength roll would be made. I make all the rolls for IOT when
 GMing your turns. I don't think I'd believe your own rolls. :)


  Physical Statistics

  Appearance:  Your physical appearance and charisma rolled into one. A
 high value increases your chance of being able to persuade people to do
 things. A high appearance is extremely useful for attracting members of
 the opposite sex. Clothing can affect the total value.
  Appearance will be known as APP from now on.

  Combat: Your ability to handle yourself in a fight. Simply, if you have
 a very low Combat, you are very bad at combat. Strength is also used in
 combat, so it is possible to make up for what you lack in combat skills
 with sheer strength alone.
  Combat will be known as COM from now on.

  Dexterity: A character's skill at using his hands. This is used whenever
 the character tries to do something like pick-pocket or lock-pick. A very
 useful statistic for Rogues and Rangers, as throwing and archery are also
 tested using the character's dexterity.
  Dexterity will be known as DEX from now on.

  Speed: Your physical speed. This statistic is often used in combat to
 dodge the enemy's blow. It would be used if you were attempting to run
 away from something, and also decides who gets the first round in a fight.

  Strength: A character's physical strength. This also contains an element
 of mental strength. It is possible to have a very high Strength without
 being massively built up. Strength is used in combat, and to do things
 like pick up heavy objects, or knock down doors. The Maniac and Warrior
 classes should have a relatively high Strength, for obvious reasons.
  Strength will be known as STR from now on.

  Hit Points, or Health: Your character's life-force. When this runs
 out, as a general rule you die. If you're in a fight, and this starts
 getting low, try to escape and get medical attention. When wounded,
 blood-loss can cause a rapid decrease in Hit Points.
  Hit Points will be known as HPs from now on.

  Mental Statistics

  Intelligence: Your character's ability to work things out in their head.
 If we're going by stereotypes, Mages have an extremely high Intelligence,
 and Maniacs have very little. This statistic also accounts for your
 character's education, and it can be increased considerably as you learn.
 Intelligence tests are usually made when trying to learn spells.
  Intelligence will be known as INT from now on.

  Mystical Force: The strength of your psychic and mystical powers.
 Mystical Force tests are very rarely made. Instead, this statistic
 decides the power of any spells you successfully cast. The one obvious
 time a Mystical Force test is made is when a Priest makes a prayer.
  Mystical Force will be known as MF from now on.

  Observance: Simply how aware you are of details in your surroundings.
 Observance rolls are very common, and mostly occur when a PC walks into a
 new location. This is an important statistic if you're worried about
 surprise attacks. A test is also made when you search a room.
  Observance will be known as OBS from now on.

  Magic Points: How much magic or mystical power you have. Casting spells
 will eventually deplete your Magic Points. When this happens you can no
 longer perform magic until you have properly rested. Magic Point tests
 should probably never happen, as there is no obvious situation in which
 they could.
  Magic Points will be known as MPs from now on.


@endnode

