@node "Law" "The Law in Tharthaal"


  The laws in Tharthaal are extremely archaic, but most are quite logical.
 For example, it is illegal to steal another's property, or murder people.
  Here is a list of some of the laws that a character is likely to come
 across. Sentences are decided by someone, but quite who depends on the
 seriousness of the offence.

  Murder: If you are caught whilst in the process of murdering someone,
 you can be punished there and then by death, or imprisoned for public
 execution. If you are witnessed murdering, or there is sufficient
 evidence to link you to a murder, you will be put on trial by the town's
 court.

  Fighting: If you are found fighting in the streets, you may be
 imprisoned for a short time and fined. Fighting indoors is NOT necessarily
 illegal, even in some public places, as the owners of the location decide
 whether or not the law will apply to their land.

  Being drunken and disorderly: If caught drunk while on the streets you
 can be imprisoned temporarily or possibly fined.

  Rape: Rape cases with significant evidence are always taken to court.
 The victim is extremely unlikely to win though.

  Acting suspiciously: If a town guard thinks he has good reason to stop
 you for acting suspiciously, he will question you and if the
 answers are not satisfactory, you can be fined or imprisoned for a short
 time.

  Insulting a guard: you can be imprisoned or fined for insulting a
 member of the town guard whilst they are on duty.

  Assaulting a guard: If you attack or retaliate against a town guard
 whilst he is on duty, it can be punished with a long period in prison, or
 execution depending on exactly who you attack, and how you do it.

  Vagrancy: Anyone found sleeping on the streets can be fined. If they can
 not pay the fine, they can be imprisoned.

  Consistently offending: If a single person is convicted of 5 or more
 crimes, he can be given long term imprisonment, or possibly be executed,
 depending on the offences. If a person commits the SAME offence 3 or more
 times, the same applies.

  Robbery or burglary: Robbery is generally punished by a short
 imprisonment and a fine. Also, stolen goods will be returned to their
 respective owners. Depending on the scale of the theft, larger penalties
 can be introduced, like chopping off the criminal's finger/hand/arm/head.

  Vandalism: Vandalism is punished by a fine double to that of the cost of
 damage done. If you are unable to pay, you can be given prolonged
 imprisonment, or worse.

  Any crimes committed that are of special relevance to the Order of Nuln
 will be passed to them if a ballot held by the Tharthaal council agrees.

  Any crimes involving magic, witchcraft, or religion are automatically
 forwarded to the Inquisition, who can choose whether to put the criminal
 on trial, or to give an instant judgement. All Inquisition trials,
 investigations and convictions should be reported by the involved
 followers, to the higher body in the Order of Nuln.


@endnode

@node "FRIENDS" "Making Friends in Tharthaal"


  Before deciding on where you want to go in Tharthaal it is a good idea
 to think about what your character is like, and likes doing. When your
 character is detailed enough to have his/her own personal taste, you will
 be able to think of the sort of places that your character likes to spend
 his/her time in.. There are many places where anyone can meet like-minded
 people in Tharthaal, it's just a matter of looking on the map, and
 talking to people, as a lot of locations are not on the map..

  Adventurers: There are many taverns in which you'll meet adventuring
 types. Ones of particular interest are: The Sword and Skull and the
 Warrior's Rest.

  Town Guard: The best place to meet members of the town guard, and king's
 militia when they are off duty, is the Guard's Arms, a large tavern that
 only lets people in that are known to the guards and militia within.

  Order of Nuln: The second great temple of Nuln is a good place to meet
 up with fellow believers, as is the Inquisition headquarters. Neither of
 these locations let you in unless you are very well known to them or a
 member of the Order..

  Wealthy citizens: If you have enough money, there are a lot of places in
 Northern Tharthaal where you can meet with fellow nobles. Young gentry
 can make friends by enrolling into the King's College, or by spending
 time in the New-Tharthaal bars.


@endnode

@node "EQUIPMENT" "Buying Equipment"


  There are many shops in Tharthaal that sell items useful to an
 adventurer. Here is a list of all the interesting shops, and what they
 sell.

  Mafri The Blacksmith's: Mafri is a skilled blacksmith, and makes quality
 weapons and other metal tools.

  The butchers: Sells meat.

  The Armoury: Sells inexpensive common weapons, and supplies weapons to
 the town guard and militia.

  The Town Stables: Sells horses, ponies, donkeys, and other riding
 animals.

  The Town Stores: Sells objects that are useful to adventurers and
 townspeople. This includes rope, torches, candles, paper, ink, spades,
 etc. etc.

  The Market Square: Sells many different objects that may or may not be
 of interest.


@endnode

@node "SLEEP" "Finding somewhere to sleep in Tharthaal"


  Finding a good place to sleep in Tharthaal is not always an easy task.
 The inns and taverns may have space, but often cost more than you're
 willing to spend. Some of them have common rooms, but these are great
 places for thieves and drunkards. The streets are dangerous at nights,
 and sleeping on them is illegal anyway. Sometimes it is possible to find
 sympathetic temples that will offer you place to sleep, but generally they
 wouldn't do that unless they knew you had good intentions or followed
 their religion.


@endnode

@node "MONEY" "Making A living In Tharthaal"


  There are many ways that you can make money in Tharthaal,
 unfortunately, as a newcomer, most of them are extremely difficult.. To
 some though, money is of no importance anyway. Here is a list of some of
 the things you could do to pass the time, and make money if necessary.

  Join the town Guard: The town guard are very welcoming towards people
 who wish to join them. You could either become a civilian official, who
 effectively spies on other townspeople, or a full-blown guard. The latter
 is more difficult, requiring around a year's training, or proof that you
 are good enough to work for them and evidence that you're not completely
 psychotic or likely to perform crimes yourself. The perks of being a
 guard are getting optional full accommodation in the guards barracks, and
 a reasonably steady wage.

  Join the king's militia: Although not everyone's idea of a good living,
 work in the militia does have some good points. First of all, the militia
 is always happy to take on new members, and has many different positions
 for workers. They require cooks, musicians, and troops of various levels
 of skill. To become a base level troop you must go through approximately
 two years of training, or have adequate experience prior to joining. The
 militia spend a lot of time outside of the town, and have recently taken
 part in battles against the Nester People of the north-west. The militia
 also have full free accommodation if required, in the militia barracks,
 and get a medium working class wage.

  Join the Order of Nuln: The Order is quite secretive about what methods
 it uses to recruit Priests and fighters, but they certainly would welcome
 volunteers. The amount of training required for a position is unknown, as
 are the wages, if any. Accommodation is definitely offered to their men
 though, in either their headquarters in south Lyona, or in the great
 northern temple.

  Join one of the other religions: Although none of the other religious
 groups are known to offer any sort of financial payment to their priests
 and volunteers, they may offer them good favour and possibly accommodation
 and food. All the religious groups in Lyona would be happy to gain more
 support, so you shouldn't have any trouble finding something of interest.
 Just make sure that you join the right religion though, as you wouldn't
 want to have to break your religious code later on.

  Become a thief!: Both southern and northern Tharthaal contain enough
 riches to keep a good thief continuously in pocket. There are major
 problems if caught though, so this probably isn't a very easy job,
 especially to those who are new to the town. There is rumoured to be a
 thieves guild within the town, that meets up to plan it's next raids,
 but nobody has been able to prove this.

  Be an adventurer: The life of the average adventurer is a surprisingly
 dull one. Generally sitting in taverns, drinking a lot, adventurers wait
 for rich businessmen and nobles to call upon them and pay them large
 amounts of gold to do odd jobs, like act as a body guard, assassinate an
 enemy, or steal an item. There are more active adventurers than this
 too, who do not quest for money or personal gain, but for justice or
 revenge. These adventurers with a cause are rare beasts indeed, and don't
 usually live very long anyway. Solely adventuring is unlikely to gain you
 enough money to live off, so getting a second income is recommended.

  Do something entirely different: There a hundreds of opportunities for
 your character in Tharthaal. All you have to do is think up some sort of
 career plan, and either seek employment, or set up on your own business.
 The latter is very unlikely, as there are very few unoccupied buildings
 in Tharthaal, and you'd have to pay quite a large sum to persuade a
 family to move out.


@endnode

@node "ADVENTURE" "Finding adventure in Thaarthaal"


  Finding adventure in Tharthaal is not usually that difficult, as there
 are always people who want work done for them. Jobs as bodyguards or
 messagers are particularly common, as are spying jobs. Adventures in the
 traditional role-play sense, by rescuing maidens, killing dragons, and
 running around in dark corridors full of Goblins, are very rare.
 Tharthaal is a city, and most adventures you'll find yourself on will be
 inside the city walls. On occasion you may find yourself outside the
 city, though, so it helps to be equipped for these circumstances.

  Here is a list of things you could do to guarantee an exciting, but
 possibly short life in Tharthaal:

  Spend time in taverns, listening for rumours, and hoping for employment.
 This is what most adventurers seem to do. You'd have to get a good
 reputation as a mercenary to get an acceptable wage though.

  Always aim all of your character's actions toward achieving a certain
 goal or ambition. A lot of adventurers quest for glory more than money,
 while others seek revenge. You must have some idea as to why you choose
 such a hazardous, and generally badly-paid job.

  Volunteer to do odd jobs for the religious groups and organisations of
 Tharthaal. The town guard and Order of Nuln in particular make use of
 civilian spies and observers.

  Join a religious group as a missionary, fighter priest, guard, or any
 other position you are interested in. There is always a lot of work to do
 as a priest of most religions, but the work can be very rewarding.

  Most of all, be observant. The most successful of adventurers do not
 wait for someone to ask them to do something. Instead, they wait and
 listen, adventuring for themselves, not some rich businessmen.


@endnode

@node "QUEST" "The New-Player Application and Generation"


  The Mystic Initiation Sheet is split into three sections: New Player
 Application, Character Generation, and Communication sections. You
 must answer all questions fully for the application to be valid.


 New Player Application:

  The information I get from the application section I can use to database
 my players, and get some idea of what they're expecting from the game, as
 well as tell what game options the players want active.


 Character Generation:

  Before filling in the Character Generation section it would be wise for
 you to read a lot, if not all, of the guide, so that you can answer the
 questions accurately and won't want to change your mind about them later.

  Using the answers you have given to these questions I will generate your
 character for use in the game, so make sure you are clear in what you
 want your character to be like.


 Communication Section:

  This is the section on which you plan your preset questions and answers.
 What you input here is used solely by the *ASK command, which is used to
 speed up communication between players.

  This section is different to the others in a few ways. I'll explain; You
 will see a list of communications or phrases, with a number by each one.
 Underneath each question there are two gaps for you to write your answers
 in. A completed example for one communication:

        Q1: What is your Name?
        C1: By what name shall I call thou?
        A1: My name is Jaarin of Itona, son of Kyanto.

  Q: This is the meaning of the question. Do NOT change this.
  C: The communication YOU make when you choose this entry number.
  A: This is the answer YOU give when asked this question number.

  When you insert a communication into the C or A column, be sure that
 there is NO line wrapping. If it has to be long, it still must on a
 single line.


 Editing the initiation sheet:


 So, I expect you'll want to fill the sheet in now. Providing you have
 one of the following editors in your path, you can edit the sheet from
 this guide by simply pressing the button for your editor. Don't worry,
 there's a backup of the application in the 'texts' directory, named
 'PlayerQuest.BLANK'. If you do not have any of these editors in your
 path, you can edit the text-file 'PlayerQuest' with whatever you please.


  @{"ANN" system "ANN texts/PlayerQuest"}
  @{"CED" system "CED texts/PlayerQuest"}
  @{"GED" system "GED texts/PlayerQuest"}
  @{"BED" system "BED texts/PlayerQuest"}


  @{"View blank Character Generation Sheet " system "multiview texts/PlayerQuest.BLANK"}
  @{"View your Character Generation Sheet " system "multiview texts/PlayerQuest"}

  @{"View example, completed Character Generation Sheet " system "multiview texts/PlayerQexam"}


@endnode

@node "ALR" "The Arcane Lore Range"


