@node "GMING" "GMing a Mystic Campaign"


  GMing a Mystic campaign is perfectly possible (I can do it, after all!),
 but not without the rules. Those interested in game mechanics will have
 realised by now that this guide contains very little of substance in the
 rules department. That's how it should be though, as the guide is
 already intimidating to a beginner. Also, I wouldn't want people
 stealing my ideas (I might run out), or using the rules against me.
 Those of you who've GM'd will know exactly what I mean. You know, that
 one player who's read the entire rule book, and knows all the statistics,
 and all of the surprises and abnormalities of the game world. I think
 I've limited the chances of getting any of these troublesome entities by
 only using this guide for universal background information and rules.
 Those aren't the only measures I've gone to to make players unfamiliar
 with their surroundings, not by a long shot. Irall Rhin has it's fair
 share of surprises and perculiarities, which may come as a shock to
 anyone expecting the stereotypical fantasy realm.

  If you wanted to GM, either in a PBM/PBEM sense, or in a traditional
 home RPG with your friends, you would need the Mystic GM's guide. The
 guide uses Irall-Rhin as it's example campaign world, but the Mystic
 system is a generic one, that can work in many separate sorts of game
 world. There are example game world ideas in the guide for the more
 imaginative GMs. Now, if you were seriously thinking of taking up GMing
 for the remotely played game, there are two ways you could go about it.
 Firstly, you could use the Insignia of Terror setting, or secondly you
 could make up and use your own campaign world. Either way, you would be
 expected to keep MFD updated on things going on in your GM territory,
 especially if you have territory in Irall Rhin, as your players could
 quite easily decide to stroll over to my GMing city of Tharthaal.

  For more information on GMing a Mystic campaign, see the GM's guide or
 contact me at any of the addresses in this guide.


@endnode

